WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.964
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:09.340 --> 00:00:12.790
SAM ZIEN: So thank
you for having me.

00:00:12.790 --> 00:00:15.840
And I appreciate
Francesca's intro.

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:18.280
I'm not trying to make
people leave their jobs.

00:00:18.280 --> 00:00:20.300
That's not the goal.

00:00:20.300 --> 00:00:23.550
It was for me.

00:00:23.550 --> 00:00:25.890
So let's see.

00:00:25.890 --> 00:00:28.140
I was never somebody
that grew up

00:00:28.140 --> 00:00:31.500
knowing what he
wanted to do in life.

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:35.100
No doctor, no teacher, no
accountant, no bus driver,

00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:39.810
no clue, like
literally, no clue.

00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:42.900
My father would take me
to see big band music.

00:00:42.900 --> 00:00:44.270
I'm from Vancouver, Canada.

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:46.590
And the intermission,
we'd stand.

00:00:46.590 --> 00:00:47.820
He'd have a cocktail.

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:50.940
And we'd just be in the lobby.

00:00:50.940 --> 00:00:53.650
And he'd say, oh, there's
Joe Smith, my friend,

00:00:53.650 --> 00:00:56.310
and there's Harry whatever.

00:00:56.310 --> 00:00:58.310
And I was always
saying, what does he do?

00:00:58.310 --> 00:00:58.990
What does he do?

00:00:58.990 --> 00:00:59.656
What does he do?

00:00:59.656 --> 00:01:02.580
I was hoping to hear something
that would catch my ear

00:01:02.580 --> 00:01:04.920
and I'd be like, that sounds
like an interesting job.

00:01:04.920 --> 00:01:06.900
I could do that.

00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:08.310
Well, that didn't work.

00:01:08.310 --> 00:01:10.490
And when it came time to
graduate from high school

00:01:10.490 --> 00:01:14.070
and go to college, I did exactly
what one of my brothers did.

00:01:14.070 --> 00:01:16.140
I went and took a
marketing program.

00:01:16.140 --> 00:01:19.530
And then I went into advertising
because that's what he did

00:01:19.530 --> 00:01:21.780
and it seemed like
a reasonable thing.

00:01:21.780 --> 00:01:24.060
Seemed sort of creative,
and I felt like maybe I

00:01:24.060 --> 00:01:26.850
had slight creative leanings.

00:01:26.850 --> 00:01:30.030
And then I started
to get bored with it.

00:01:30.030 --> 00:01:33.955
I got engaged to
my now wife, which

00:01:33.955 --> 00:01:36.330
makes it sound like there was
another wife along the way.

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:37.590
That's not what I meant.

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:39.090
We've been married a long time.

00:01:39.090 --> 00:01:40.770
And we moved to Toronto.

00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:43.567
I worked for an
advertising agency

00:01:43.567 --> 00:01:45.150
that wouldn't hire
me in the beginning

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:46.450
because I didn't
have any experience.

00:01:46.450 --> 00:01:48.060
And finally, I said
to them one day,

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:49.562
we've had three interviews.

00:01:49.562 --> 00:01:51.270
I'd love to be here
and you're telling me

00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:52.560
I don't have any experience.

00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:54.840
So let's do this.

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:58.230
Hire me for three
months and don't pay me.

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:00.930
At the end of three months,
if you think I'm useless,

00:02:00.930 --> 00:02:02.010
you say goodbye.

00:02:02.010 --> 00:02:04.320
I haven't cost you a cent.

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:07.350
But if at the end of three
months you think I'm useful,

00:02:07.350 --> 00:02:08.449
then you start paying me.

00:02:08.449 --> 00:02:11.550
And not only do I
know the business,

00:02:11.550 --> 00:02:14.820
but I know your
particular business.

00:02:14.820 --> 00:02:16.350
I know where the copier is.

00:02:16.350 --> 00:02:19.350
I know how to get to
the client's offices.

00:02:19.350 --> 00:02:20.980
I know what goes on here.

00:02:20.980 --> 00:02:23.714
And they said, well,
let's think about it.

00:02:23.714 --> 00:02:24.630
They took the weekend.

00:02:24.630 --> 00:02:27.280
They called back and they said,
OK, we're going to hire you.

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:29.240
So they hired me
without paying me.

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:30.990
And at the end of three
months, they said,

00:02:30.990 --> 00:02:32.392
this has gone really well.

00:02:32.392 --> 00:02:34.350
We'd like to hire you
now and start paying you.

00:02:34.350 --> 00:02:36.960
I said, that's very cool,
but one of your clients

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:38.580
just made me an
offer and I said yes.

00:02:38.580 --> 00:02:41.490
So I start there on the
weekend or next week.

00:02:41.490 --> 00:02:43.620
So now, I was the employee.

00:02:43.620 --> 00:02:48.350
Now, I became the
client and it was great.

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:52.080
It was a marketing position
in a sporting goods company

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:55.560
in Toronto that got
sold to a French parent

00:02:55.560 --> 00:02:57.300
company in Montreal.

00:02:57.300 --> 00:02:59.970
They wanted me and my wife to
move to Montreal and neither

00:02:59.970 --> 00:03:01.240
of us speak French.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:04.740
And then-- this is
30-ish years ago--

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:08.940
not speaking French in
Montreal was a bit of a hassle.

00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:10.709
It really limited
what you could do.

00:03:10.709 --> 00:03:12.000
AUDIENCE: Outside of Montreal--

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.380
SAM ZIEN: Anyway.

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:15.790
I love the French.

00:03:15.790 --> 00:03:17.840
And I like the real French too.

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:19.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:20.230
So I said no.

00:03:20.230 --> 00:03:20.970
I said no.

00:03:20.970 --> 00:03:22.230
And that's how they feel.

00:03:22.230 --> 00:03:24.990
The real French look down
on the French Canadians.

00:03:24.990 --> 00:03:27.620
And the French Canadians
are pissed about it.

00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:30.570
But so we chose not to go.

00:03:30.570 --> 00:03:34.200
And I go, now I can do what
I've really wanted to do.

00:03:34.200 --> 00:03:36.505
I want to be in film.

00:03:36.505 --> 00:03:39.900
Not in front of the camera, I
wanted to be behind the camera.

00:03:39.900 --> 00:03:42.300
So I got a job as a
production assistant

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:44.760
at a production
company in Toronto.

00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:47.640
And remember, Toronto
is a huge home

00:03:47.640 --> 00:03:52.290
to tons of movie, film,
and television in Canada.

00:03:52.290 --> 00:03:55.030
Big industry, but it also looks
like a bunch of big cities.

00:03:55.030 --> 00:03:57.540
So you pick Toronto,
you pay Canadian wages.

00:03:57.540 --> 00:03:59.370
The dollars are less up there.

00:03:59.370 --> 00:04:01.360
The production crews
are just as good.

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:03.450
And it looks like New York
or Detroit or whatever.

00:04:03.450 --> 00:04:05.860
So I did that.

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:07.560
It was just the worst
job in the world,

00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:10.140
being a production assistant,
because it's literally

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:13.160
the worst stuff they can
think of to make you do.

00:04:13.160 --> 00:04:16.860
Oh, the actor's dog just
took a crap over there.

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:18.329
Can you get that?

00:04:18.329 --> 00:04:20.430
We need some dry
cleaning taken in.

00:04:20.430 --> 00:04:23.810
We need this cable walked
four miles down the street.

00:04:23.810 --> 00:04:25.450
It was just awful.

00:04:25.450 --> 00:04:26.240
So I did that.

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:28.370
It was not nearly as
glamorous as I hoped.

00:04:28.370 --> 00:04:32.010
And in that time, my advertising
brother called up and he says,

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:36.150
one of our clients, place
called Penguin's Frozen Yogurt,

00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:37.452
is doing really well.

00:04:37.452 --> 00:04:39.660
How do you feel about us
going into the frozen yogurt

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:40.480
business?

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:42.900
I was like, yes, in two seconds.

00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:45.280
And we're going to do it in
Phoenix, even more exciting.

00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:46.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:49.650
Get out of that horrible,
horrible Toronto weather,

00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:51.590
go to Phoenix, do something new.

00:04:51.590 --> 00:04:53.490
So I started off
marketing, then ended up

00:04:53.490 --> 00:04:57.330
in an advertising agency, then
end up in the movie thing.

00:04:57.330 --> 00:05:00.960
And then before I go to frozen
yogurt, I quit the movie thing.

00:05:00.960 --> 00:05:05.960
I deliver pizzas in
Toronto for a few months.

00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:07.060
We go to Phoenix.

00:05:07.060 --> 00:05:09.150
We open up a Penguin's
Frozen Yogurt.

00:05:09.150 --> 00:05:10.110
It's going great.

00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:13.140
Some guy that has the rights
to Penguin's in Tucson

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:15.210
wants to buy the Phoenix market.

00:05:15.210 --> 00:05:16.310
He buys it from us.

00:05:16.310 --> 00:05:18.750
We just break even, don't
really make any money.

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:19.639
Now what do I do?

00:05:19.639 --> 00:05:21.180
Now, I have nothing
to do and I still

00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:23.820
don't know what I want
to do when I grow up.

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:25.890
So now what?

00:05:25.890 --> 00:05:29.100
So I did what many
people do when they don't

00:05:29.100 --> 00:05:30.780
know what they want to do.

00:05:30.780 --> 00:05:33.140
I went into real estate.

00:05:33.140 --> 00:05:34.740
It's an admirable profession.

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:38.940
I hated it, but I did it.

00:05:38.940 --> 00:05:41.790
I got my license in Arizona.

00:05:41.790 --> 00:05:43.620
And the day the license
came in the mail,

00:05:43.620 --> 00:05:45.690
we decided to move to
California because we

00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:46.950
had some family in San Diego.

00:05:46.950 --> 00:05:49.170
We came here, got my
California license.

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:50.960
It was much more
difficult than Arizona.

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:53.470
If you're going to get your
license, go to Arizona.

00:05:53.470 --> 00:05:55.570
It's easier than it
is in California.

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:59.130
Sold houses for five years,
couldn't stand a second of it.

00:05:59.130 --> 00:06:00.520
Hated it.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:03.780
I said to myself, something
good will come of this one day,

00:06:03.780 --> 00:06:05.210
I honestly believe.

00:06:05.210 --> 00:06:10.072
Finally, I sold a house to a guy
who started a biotech company--

00:06:10.072 --> 00:06:11.280
worked for a biotech company.

00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:11.850
Sold him a house.

00:06:11.850 --> 00:06:12.870
Called me up a
couple years later.

00:06:12.870 --> 00:06:15.030
He goes, I'm starting
my own biotech company.

00:06:15.030 --> 00:06:17.140
Can you help me with
a commercial property?

00:06:17.140 --> 00:06:18.292
I said, yes.

00:06:18.292 --> 00:06:20.250
I didn't know anything
about it, but my manager

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:21.580
told me he'd help me.

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:26.370
And in that process, he says,
I like working with you.

00:06:26.370 --> 00:06:27.240
We get along.

00:06:27.240 --> 00:06:28.620
This is a good relationship.

00:06:28.620 --> 00:06:30.274
Come work for the
biotech company.

00:06:30.274 --> 00:06:31.440
I go, what am I going to do?

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:33.040
I don't know anything
about biotech.

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:34.560
He goes, you'll be the director.

00:06:34.560 --> 00:06:36.330
You'll be the
facilities manager.

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:38.825
You know real
estate, construction.

00:06:38.825 --> 00:06:39.450
It'll work out.

00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:40.600
It'll be fine, blah, blah, blah.

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:42.266
So I go to work for
the biotech company.

00:06:42.266 --> 00:06:45.900
I love it for five years and
then I start to hate it again.

00:06:45.900 --> 00:06:47.550
It was the classic
three bears thing.

00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:50.610
I could not find anything
I was comfortable doing.

00:06:50.610 --> 00:06:52.590
And this is not rare.

00:06:52.590 --> 00:06:54.450
I don't know how many
of you in this room

00:06:54.450 --> 00:06:58.780
grew up knowing you wanted to
be a geek and work at Google.

00:06:58.780 --> 00:07:00.630
I mean, when I grew up
there wasn't Google.

00:07:00.630 --> 00:07:01.463
There weren't geeks.

00:07:03.780 --> 00:07:06.780
And I mean that in the
nicest way possible.

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:08.711
I didn't just wreck this, did I?

00:07:08.711 --> 00:07:09.210
Come on.

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:10.350
You guys all know it.

00:07:10.350 --> 00:07:12.680
You can't not work here and--

00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:13.880
OK.

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:15.630
So I go, something
good will come of this.

00:07:15.630 --> 00:07:16.963
Now, I'm in the biotech company.

00:07:16.963 --> 00:07:17.910
I can't stand it.

00:07:17.910 --> 00:07:18.840
Can't stand it.

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:22.520
And now, I'm at home on Sundays
with the "San Diego Union"

00:07:22.520 --> 00:07:27.390
help wanted general ad section
in front of me, cup of coffee

00:07:27.390 --> 00:07:28.200
in one hand.

00:07:28.200 --> 00:07:32.460
And now, I'm going
down the columns.

00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:33.900
Help wanted general.

00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:35.910
I'm looking for a career.

00:07:35.910 --> 00:07:39.840
Help wanted general--
accounting, advertising,

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:42.720
automotive, banking, brake
alignment, bookkeeping,

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:45.720
candy making, cookie
thing, dance instructor,

00:07:45.720 --> 00:07:46.600
delivery driver.

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:48.270
I mean, I could do
the whole alphabet.

00:07:48.270 --> 00:07:50.470
And I was waiting for
divine intervention.

00:07:50.470 --> 00:07:52.770
I imagined one day
my finger would

00:07:52.770 --> 00:07:55.150
hit a job title or description.

00:07:55.150 --> 00:07:56.110
I'd get a little chill.

00:07:56.110 --> 00:07:58.650
It would be God talking
to me, saying, Sam,

00:07:58.650 --> 00:07:59.790
this is what you should do.

00:07:59.790 --> 00:08:02.530
And I'm going to tell
you, it didn't happen.

00:08:02.530 --> 00:08:04.080
It doesn't happen like that.

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:06.450
I might as well have
been throwing darts

00:08:06.450 --> 00:08:10.931
against a board with
job titles on it.

00:08:10.931 --> 00:08:12.930
So now, I'm sitting in
my biotech office one day

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:14.190
and I'm mulling over this.

00:08:14.190 --> 00:08:15.740
I'm very upset.

00:08:15.740 --> 00:08:16.740
I can't figure this out.

00:08:16.740 --> 00:08:17.410
I'm miserable.

00:08:17.410 --> 00:08:17.910
I'm unhappy.

00:08:17.910 --> 00:08:20.660
And I say to myself, I'm going
about this the wrong way.

00:08:20.660 --> 00:08:23.910
I'm literally trying
to take my square peg

00:08:23.910 --> 00:08:27.990
and cram it into a round hole,
and that's not the thing to do.

00:08:27.990 --> 00:08:31.270
So what if somebody walked in
my office door and said to me,

00:08:31.270 --> 00:08:33.900
OK, you can go do
anything you want

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:36.179
for a living, no
regard for making

00:08:36.179 --> 00:08:39.099
money, what people thought,
providing for your family.

00:08:39.099 --> 00:08:40.890
What's the thing that
you would want to do?

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:42.210
Answer it quick, Sam.

00:08:42.210 --> 00:08:43.919
And my answer
instantly was I wanted

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:47.700
to go back to Tokyo where
I'd been a year before.

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:49.320
My brother-in-law
went on business.

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:52.800
I went for my 40th
birthday to myself.

00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:54.330
And I know what you're thinking.

00:08:54.330 --> 00:08:56.315
He's already past 40?

00:08:56.315 --> 00:08:57.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:57.010 --> 00:08:58.030
Joking.

00:08:58.030 --> 00:08:59.630
So I want to go back to Tokyo.

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:02.320
And I'm a fairly practical,
pragmatic person.

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:03.960
So at that moment,
I start trying

00:09:03.960 --> 00:09:08.020
to figure out how to get myself
back to Tokyo for a career now,

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:10.110
not just a vacay.

00:09:10.110 --> 00:09:12.010
I could become a pilot
or flight attendant,

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:14.380
but I don't really like
to fly all that much.

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:16.170
I get sick on planes.

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:17.680
And God knows, I
don't want to have

00:09:17.680 --> 00:09:19.290
to be nice to a
group of strangers

00:09:19.290 --> 00:09:21.890
for like 14 hours at a time.

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:23.550
And have you seen
how people treat

00:09:23.550 --> 00:09:26.850
flight crew on an airplane?

00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:29.620
They're basically snapping their
fingers and they're rude as F,

00:09:29.620 --> 00:09:31.530
and it's awful.

00:09:31.530 --> 00:09:34.050
So I don't want to do that.

00:09:34.050 --> 00:09:36.100
I could teach English
as a second language.

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:37.050
I come from Canada.

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:38.970
I believe I have a
pretty damn good command

00:09:38.970 --> 00:09:40.050
of the English language.

00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:41.707
I do speak the Queen's English.

00:09:41.707 --> 00:09:43.290
But the idea of
coming home and saying

00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:46.470
to my wife and three sons,
we're moving to Tokyo,

00:09:46.470 --> 00:09:49.080
we're going to live
in 14 square feet,

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:51.801
we'll sleep standing up because
laying down is overrated,

00:09:51.801 --> 00:09:52.800
it's going to be great--

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:54.780
that wasn't going to work.

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:58.110
And literally, that moment,
as I'm thinking this,

00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:01.590
I'm also thinking about
a horrible newscast,

00:10:01.590 --> 00:10:05.400
local newscast I'd
seen the night before.

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:10.274
Like wait a minute, what if
I did a kind of travel thing?

00:10:10.274 --> 00:10:11.940
Because when I came
back and told people

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:14.940
that I spent most of my time
in Tokyo alone, certainly

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:17.390
during the day, my
friends were like,

00:10:17.390 --> 00:10:19.024
I don't know if I
could do that, dude.

00:10:19.024 --> 00:10:20.190
You can't read the language.

00:10:20.190 --> 00:10:21.420
You don't know what the food is.

00:10:21.420 --> 00:10:22.420
You can't get the signs.

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:23.567
You can't understand.

00:10:23.567 --> 00:10:25.150
But for me, that was
kind of exciting.

00:10:25.150 --> 00:10:26.580
I thought, maybe
I could do that.

00:10:26.580 --> 00:10:31.530
And within about 15 minutes,
I had thunk up a perfect job.

00:10:31.530 --> 00:10:33.900
I would go to foreign locations.

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:35.250
I would shoot some footage.

00:10:35.250 --> 00:10:38.400
I'd put together a
little travel series.

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:41.220
I would come back and I
would air three or four

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:44.349
minutes a night on a
local news channel.

00:10:44.349 --> 00:10:46.140
(NEWSCASTER VOICE) Stay
tuned all next week

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:49.500
while our travel guy shows you
the ins and outs of Tokyo--

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:52.020
or Hong Kong or
Bali or whatever.

00:10:52.020 --> 00:10:53.260
It was a great idea.

00:10:53.260 --> 00:10:55.830
I quit my biotech
job, say goodbye.

00:10:55.830 --> 00:10:57.300
See ya, suckers.

00:10:57.300 --> 00:10:58.960
I'm out of here.

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:00.420
I was so excited.

00:11:00.420 --> 00:11:01.830
Pulled together
this little crew.

00:11:01.830 --> 00:11:04.020
Nobody's getting paid,
but we're getting a trip

00:11:04.020 --> 00:11:06.810
to Tokyo and Hong Kong
to shoot demo footage.

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:11.700
I'd managed to convince the Hong
Kong tourist board and a hotel

00:11:11.700 --> 00:11:15.030
association in Japan to
sort of underwrite the trip.

00:11:15.030 --> 00:11:16.950
Nobody gets money,
but we get flights

00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:18.790
and travel and accommodation.

00:11:18.790 --> 00:11:20.280
It's great.

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:24.240
All excited, things
are going beautifully,

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:26.320
until a month before
we're supposed to go,

00:11:26.320 --> 00:11:28.620
and 9/11 happens.

00:11:28.620 --> 00:11:32.010
And I always tell this part of
the story the exact same way.

00:11:32.010 --> 00:11:34.260
I say, that day
changed thousands

00:11:34.260 --> 00:11:36.690
of other people's lives
much more significantly

00:11:36.690 --> 00:11:38.460
than it changed mine.

00:11:38.460 --> 00:11:42.390
But it still changed my life
because after September 11

00:11:42.390 --> 00:11:45.450
of 2001, nobody was
buying a travel show.

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:47.760
Nobody was getting on planes.

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:50.160
Nobody was buying a
travel show, especially

00:11:50.160 --> 00:11:53.100
from a guy who barely
had ever traveled

00:11:53.100 --> 00:11:55.680
and certainly had never
been on television.

00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:57.780
What was I thinking?

00:11:57.780 --> 00:12:00.250
Well, I was thinking that
I wanted to be happy.

00:12:00.250 --> 00:12:01.650
That's what I was thinking.

00:12:01.650 --> 00:12:04.650
So now, September
11 comes and goes.

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:06.840
It's literally the week after.

00:12:06.840 --> 00:12:09.060
I'm sitting now in that
same spot on the couch

00:12:09.060 --> 00:12:10.860
where I'm going
through the newspaper.

00:12:10.860 --> 00:12:16.020
And my wife goes to work and she
says, what are you going to do?

00:12:16.020 --> 00:12:17.640
I go, I don't know.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:19.050
I don't know.

00:12:19.050 --> 00:12:21.510
I wanted to encourage
people to travel,

00:12:21.510 --> 00:12:22.800
do something they hadn't done.

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:27.100
And I liked that idea, but
what could I do with that?

00:12:27.100 --> 00:12:28.410
So one day she goes to work.

00:12:28.410 --> 00:12:30.300
I'm watching KUSI.

00:12:30.300 --> 00:12:32.430
And on comes the
worst cooking segment

00:12:32.430 --> 00:12:33.990
I've ever seen in my life.

00:12:33.990 --> 00:12:35.745
I'm telling you,
it was horrific.

00:12:38.250 --> 00:12:42.270
The chef, who could probably
kick my ass all over a kitchen,

00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:44.220
was as boring as they came.

00:12:44.220 --> 00:12:45.810
But he didn't need
to be exciting.

00:12:45.810 --> 00:12:47.340
He's in the back, cooking food.

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:48.600
He's wearing his chef whites.

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:51.120
The anchors couldn't
pronounce creme fraiche.

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:52.230
It was idiotic.

00:12:52.230 --> 00:12:53.190
It was boring.

00:12:53.190 --> 00:12:56.880
The camera stayed on this
pot of butternut squash soup

00:12:56.880 --> 00:12:59.760
for like a solid
30 plus seconds.

00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:01.800
I go, this is awful television.

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:03.222
Somebody should do this better.

00:13:03.222 --> 00:13:04.805
And then bing, there's
the light bulb.

00:13:04.805 --> 00:13:07.234
And I go, crap, I
should do this better.

00:13:07.234 --> 00:13:08.400
My wife comes home that day.

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:09.695
I go, I've got it.

00:13:09.695 --> 00:13:10.320
She goes, what?

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:13.520
I go, cooking show.

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:15.170
Instead of short
travel segments,

00:13:15.170 --> 00:13:16.970
I'll do short cooking segments.

00:13:16.970 --> 00:13:20.120
She goes, I think that's a
fantastic idea, just one thing.

00:13:20.120 --> 00:13:20.620
I go, what?

00:13:20.620 --> 00:13:21.860
She goes, you can't cook.

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:22.670
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:22.670 --> 00:13:24.410
I go, well, here's the thing.

00:13:24.410 --> 00:13:26.600
Instead of watching a
cooking segment thinking that

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:30.530
looks good and complicated, but
now I'm hungry, let's go out,

00:13:30.530 --> 00:13:33.530
people will watch and go,
that looks good and easy.

00:13:33.530 --> 00:13:36.180
I'll be my own weakest link.

00:13:36.180 --> 00:13:38.000
I can make that.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.820
Now, my wife in all of
this, you have to understand

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:44.060
is the real genius
because in her mind,

00:13:44.060 --> 00:13:47.360
there was no way that the travel
thing was ever going to work.

00:13:47.360 --> 00:13:49.120
But what it was
going to do, it was

00:13:49.120 --> 00:13:50.870
going to get me out
of the biotech company

00:13:50.870 --> 00:13:52.710
where I was very comfortable.

00:13:52.710 --> 00:13:53.214
I was safe.

00:13:53.214 --> 00:13:55.130
And it's like, I was in
my bed in the morning,

00:13:55.130 --> 00:13:56.300
the covers around my neck.

00:13:56.300 --> 00:13:57.260
It was cozy.

00:13:57.260 --> 00:13:58.610
I didn't want to get up.

00:13:58.610 --> 00:13:59.900
I needed something.

00:13:59.900 --> 00:14:02.510
I needed a life kick in the ass.

00:14:02.510 --> 00:14:04.782
She knew the travel
thing wouldn't work,

00:14:04.782 --> 00:14:06.740
but then two, three months
later, there I'd be.

00:14:06.740 --> 00:14:10.370
Now, I'd be forced
to find something.

00:14:10.370 --> 00:14:12.730
So travel goes, cooking comes.

00:14:12.730 --> 00:14:14.680
She's still thinking
the same thing.

00:14:14.680 --> 00:14:16.960
I call the crew, I go, boys--

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:17.980
because it was only men.

00:14:17.980 --> 00:14:20.140
There would be women
today, I promise.

00:14:20.140 --> 00:14:22.180
I've worked with a lot
of really talented women,

00:14:22.180 --> 00:14:23.737
but it was only guys then.

00:14:23.737 --> 00:14:25.570
I go, we're not going
to Tokyo or Hong Kong.

00:14:25.570 --> 00:14:26.986
We're going to
shoot in my kitchen

00:14:26.986 --> 00:14:28.930
and make a little cooking thing.

00:14:28.930 --> 00:14:31.460
We shot, put it together.

00:14:31.460 --> 00:14:35.140
I'm telling you,
you're going to see it.

00:14:35.140 --> 00:14:38.290
It was my "Gone with the
Wind," my "Godfather"--

00:14:38.290 --> 00:14:42.400
I like that-- my "Godfather."

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:43.150
So we'll watch it.

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:46.281
And just know, there's a
little stutter for those of you

00:14:46.281 --> 00:14:46.780
in the room.

00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:49.000
People watching this after
the fact will see it fine.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:52.510
So now, understand is Sam
the cooking guy before he

00:14:52.510 --> 00:14:54.460
was really Sam the cooking guy.

00:14:54.460 --> 00:14:58.180
And I want you to try
and notice the mistakes.

00:14:58.180 --> 00:15:01.374
You'll see the shadow
of the camera guy's head

00:15:01.374 --> 00:15:02.290
on one of my cabinets.

00:15:02.290 --> 00:15:03.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:03.250 --> 00:15:06.760
There's a shot out the window
and there's a big C stand

00:15:06.760 --> 00:15:10.810
that they use to hold equipment
that had tarps and junk on it.

00:15:10.810 --> 00:15:13.150
And I can't find
my whisk in this.

00:15:13.150 --> 00:15:15.270
The guy says, let's
cut that part out.

00:15:15.270 --> 00:15:17.215
And I go, no, it feels
kind of authentic.

00:15:17.215 --> 00:15:17.840
We'll leave it.

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:20.440
So this is me before me was me.

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:21.314
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:21.314 --> 00:15:22.190
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:15:22.190 --> 00:15:24.440
- Hi, I'm Sam, the cooking guy.

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:26.720
Today, we're going to make
lemon teriyaki salmon.

00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:29.360
I call it rainy day salmon
because back home, we

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:31.800
used to make it on
rainy days all the time.

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:33.540
And it takes no time at all.

00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:36.800
We start very
simply with one pot.

00:15:36.800 --> 00:15:39.560
We're going to put the following
seven ingredients into it.

00:15:39.560 --> 00:15:41.150
Soy sauce, 1/2 cup.

00:15:41.150 --> 00:15:42.260
1/4 cup of sake.

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:45.140
If you don't have
this, you should

00:15:45.140 --> 00:15:48.250
because it's great to drink and
it's excellent to cook with.

00:15:48.250 --> 00:15:54.160
1/3 cup sugar, teaspoon of
mint ginger, clove of garlic,

00:15:54.160 --> 00:15:56.660
juice of one whole lemon--

00:15:56.660 --> 00:16:00.290
juice going everywhere--
a teaspoon of dry mustard.

00:16:00.290 --> 00:16:01.094
We're done.

00:16:01.094 --> 00:16:03.260
We're going to put this on
the stove for 10 minutes,

00:16:03.260 --> 00:16:04.220
let it simmer.

00:16:04.220 --> 00:16:06.800
In that time, we're going to
heat the oven, cut our salmon,

00:16:06.800 --> 00:16:08.450
and we're almost set.

00:16:08.450 --> 00:16:11.960
Really, it only needs to be
there for maybe 10 minutes

00:16:11.960 --> 00:16:13.307
maximum.

00:16:13.307 --> 00:16:15.140
You just want it to
thicken up a little bit.

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:16.315
Grab my whisk.

00:16:16.315 --> 00:16:17.630
OK, hang on.

00:16:17.630 --> 00:16:20.600
I can't find my whisk.

00:16:20.600 --> 00:16:22.190
OK, we're not going
to use a whisk.

00:16:22.190 --> 00:16:23.880
You just need to stir it around.

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:26.380
All we're going to do now
is we're going to baste it.

00:16:26.380 --> 00:16:28.940
It doesn't get any easier
than this, honestly.

00:16:28.940 --> 00:16:31.640
We're going to pop
this under the broiler.

00:16:31.640 --> 00:16:34.640
Five minutes on this side, five
on other side, and that's it.

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:37.994
If you bring this salmon to
the table looking like this,

00:16:37.994 --> 00:16:39.410
people are going
to be blown away.

00:16:39.410 --> 00:16:41.294
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING]

00:16:44.120 --> 00:16:45.200
I amaze even myself.

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:46.870
My mom would be really proud.

00:16:46.870 --> 00:16:48.470
Rainy day salmon.

00:16:48.470 --> 00:16:49.910
I'm the cooking guy.

00:16:49.910 --> 00:16:51.048
I'll see you next time.

00:16:51.048 --> 00:16:52.720
[END PLAYBACK]

00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:54.690
So look, anything--

00:16:54.690 --> 00:16:55.190
[CLAPPING]

00:16:55.190 --> 00:16:56.870
Oh, please don't clap for that.

00:16:56.870 --> 00:16:58.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:58.850 --> 00:16:59.810
It's like anything.

00:16:59.810 --> 00:17:03.140
The first time you do it,
you're maybe OK at it.

00:17:03.140 --> 00:17:04.430
The 10th time, you get better.

00:17:04.430 --> 00:17:06.644
It really took me a
while to find my voice.

00:17:06.644 --> 00:17:08.310
AUDIENCE: Maybe your
accent was thicker.

00:17:08.310 --> 00:17:09.661
SAM ZIEN: It was thicker, yeah.

00:17:09.661 --> 00:17:10.160
It was.

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:11.420
It was 15 years ago.

00:17:11.420 --> 00:17:12.400
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:14.960
I might not have said
any O-U words yet.

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:16.710
I'll get there.

00:17:16.710 --> 00:17:18.500
So we take that demo
and I send it out.

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:22.040
I managed to put
together five names

00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:23.790
of people in the industry.

00:17:23.790 --> 00:17:26.690
My ultimate goal,
our local stations.

00:17:26.690 --> 00:17:28.670
The idea was like, make
it once and sell it

00:17:28.670 --> 00:17:30.484
1,000 times around the country.

00:17:30.484 --> 00:17:32.150
But I don't want to
go to local stations

00:17:32.150 --> 00:17:35.090
first because if they
hate it, they're not going

00:17:35.090 --> 00:17:37.010
to watch it if I get it fixed.

00:17:37.010 --> 00:17:37.864
By the way, hi.

00:17:37.864 --> 00:17:38.780
You just came in late.

00:17:38.780 --> 00:17:40.363
You missed a lot of
really good stuff.

00:17:40.363 --> 00:17:41.210
I'm sorry.

00:17:41.210 --> 00:17:42.290
Really good stuff.

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:44.600
And I've given out really
good prizes so far.

00:17:44.600 --> 00:17:47.780
The next person's talk, you
might want to come earlier.

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:52.310
So I don't want to send
it to a local station

00:17:52.310 --> 00:17:55.700
because they're not going to
watch it a second time if I

00:17:55.700 --> 00:17:57.140
figured out that it blows.

00:17:57.140 --> 00:18:00.230
So I send it to outside people.

00:18:00.230 --> 00:18:01.370
Nobody likes it.

00:18:01.370 --> 00:18:05.260
One guy from Tribune Media
in Chicago actually says--

00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:07.580
can I swear?

00:18:07.580 --> 00:18:09.110
I'll just say the letter.

00:18:09.110 --> 00:18:13.319
He actually said, you don't
have an effing chance.

00:18:13.319 --> 00:18:14.360
But he didn't say effing.

00:18:14.360 --> 00:18:15.500
He said the whole word.

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:18.660
Can you believe that somebody
would say that to you?

00:18:18.660 --> 00:18:19.540
Can you?

00:18:19.540 --> 00:18:21.360
So I said, all right,
now I'm so pissed.

00:18:21.360 --> 00:18:23.750
Now, I am going to send it
to a couple local stations

00:18:23.750 --> 00:18:26.110
and see what their reaction is.

00:18:26.110 --> 00:18:30.440
I sent it to two stations in San
Diego, channel 7, the NBC guys.

00:18:30.440 --> 00:18:34.220
Was rejected by a really
lovely English woman.

00:18:34.220 --> 00:18:37.455
And you know the Brits can
make anything sound good.

00:18:37.455 --> 00:18:38.830
(BRITISH ACCENT)
Hello, Mr. Zien.

00:18:38.830 --> 00:18:40.120
We got your tape.

00:18:40.120 --> 00:18:41.930
It's lovely.

00:18:41.930 --> 00:18:46.350
It's just not right
for us at this time.

00:18:46.350 --> 00:18:47.990
OK, I feel good actually.

00:18:47.990 --> 00:18:48.710
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:48.710 --> 00:18:50.280
I don't know why I feel good.

00:18:50.280 --> 00:18:53.029
A doctor could come in, you go
in with a pain in your knee--

00:18:53.029 --> 00:18:55.320
(BRITISH ACCENT) Mr. Zien,
we had a look at the X-rays.

00:18:55.320 --> 00:18:57.932
We've got to amputate your head.

00:18:57.932 --> 00:18:59.219
Oh, OK.

00:18:59.219 --> 00:19:00.260
Do you want to do it now?

00:19:00.260 --> 00:19:01.314
You want me to come back?

00:19:01.314 --> 00:19:02.480
What's good for your sched--

00:19:02.480 --> 00:19:03.170
right?

00:19:03.170 --> 00:19:03.930
It's crazy.

00:19:03.930 --> 00:19:07.730
I also sent it to channel 6,
which then was a Fox station.

00:19:07.730 --> 00:19:11.300
I get a phone call back a
month later from a guy named

00:19:11.300 --> 00:19:18.230
Alberto Pando, the vice
president of programming.

00:19:18.230 --> 00:19:20.220
He says, so here's the thing.

00:19:20.220 --> 00:19:21.170
I got your tape.

00:19:21.170 --> 00:19:22.280
I put it in.

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:24.125
I watched it.

00:19:24.125 --> 00:19:25.250
He goes, I really liked it.

00:19:25.250 --> 00:19:27.980
He goes, you're kind
of like a little odd--

00:19:27.980 --> 00:19:28.940
what you guys watched.

00:19:28.940 --> 00:19:30.100
That made me odd.

00:19:30.100 --> 00:19:33.270
Goes, you're a little odd, but
we'd love to talk with you.

00:19:33.270 --> 00:19:35.090
So I go in.

00:19:35.090 --> 00:19:40.190
They put me on TV twice a
week doing a 90-second segment

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:44.539
on their morning news,
Monday and Friday.

00:19:44.539 --> 00:19:45.080
Unbelievable.

00:19:45.080 --> 00:19:46.186
Here's the first one.

00:19:46.186 --> 00:19:47.060
Here's the first one.

00:19:47.060 --> 00:19:48.530
So I go that first day.

00:19:48.530 --> 00:19:51.020
I'm going to be on
at like 10 to 8:00.

00:19:51.020 --> 00:19:55.400
The guy comes in
about quarter to 8:00.

00:19:55.400 --> 00:19:57.590
I'm in the green room,
which-- they're never green,

00:19:57.590 --> 00:19:59.261
by the way.

00:19:59.261 --> 00:20:01.260
And he goes, we've got
to bump you a little bit.

00:20:01.260 --> 00:20:02.884
And I go, uh oh, here it comes.

00:20:02.884 --> 00:20:03.800
They watched it again.

00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:05.027
They realized I'm a fake.

00:20:05.027 --> 00:20:06.110
They're not putting me on.

00:20:06.110 --> 00:20:07.490
He goes no, no, no.

00:20:07.490 --> 00:20:09.640
We just need to
put you 10 after.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:11.600
And I think he could
see how nervous I was.

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:14.810
I mean, honestly, my heart
was moving in and out

00:20:14.810 --> 00:20:16.280
of my sweater.

00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:17.990
So he took me into
the control room

00:20:17.990 --> 00:20:20.090
where I could see
the studio behind me.

00:20:20.090 --> 00:20:22.670
I could see the big
board and all the TVs

00:20:22.670 --> 00:20:24.110
and stuff they look at.

00:20:24.110 --> 00:20:25.029
And it calmed me down.

00:20:25.029 --> 00:20:25.820
And then I went in.

00:20:25.820 --> 00:20:29.370
So this is me.

00:20:29.370 --> 00:20:32.360
This is January, February
March, April, May--

00:20:32.360 --> 00:20:34.930
May of 2002.

00:20:34.930 --> 00:20:35.770
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:20:35.770 --> 00:20:39.205
- And that's where the
cooking guy comes in.

00:20:39.205 --> 00:20:41.020
- Hi, I'm Sam, the cooking guy.

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:43.960
And today, we're going to make a
very delicious barbecue chicken

00:20:43.960 --> 00:20:44.710
pizza.

00:20:44.710 --> 00:20:48.670
The difference is, we're not
going to use this to make it.

00:20:48.670 --> 00:20:49.760
We're going to use these.

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:52.210
Put your oven, 450 degrees.

00:20:52.210 --> 00:20:53.570
Get it good and hot.

00:20:53.570 --> 00:20:57.190
I like to start with a 10-ounce
Italian crust, bought it

00:20:57.190 --> 00:20:58.090
from the store.

00:20:58.090 --> 00:21:00.610
We're going to take and we're
going to brush barbecue sauce

00:21:00.610 --> 00:21:02.860
on the crust, just about--

00:21:02.860 --> 00:21:05.440
oh, I don't know-- about 2
tablespoons' worth of it.

00:21:05.440 --> 00:21:08.650
On top of that, we're
going to put maybe 1/4

00:21:08.650 --> 00:21:11.300
cup of smoked gouda cheese.

00:21:11.300 --> 00:21:13.540
I've got 2 cups of
shredded chicken.

00:21:13.540 --> 00:21:16.150
I bought a deli roasted
chicken at the supermarket.

00:21:16.150 --> 00:21:17.200
You can make your own.

00:21:17.200 --> 00:21:18.380
This is much easier.

00:21:18.380 --> 00:21:20.800
I've mixed it with a couple
tablespoons of barbecue sauce

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:21.710
as well.

00:21:21.710 --> 00:21:24.310
This is going on top.

00:21:24.310 --> 00:21:26.770
Spread it around
with your hands.

00:21:26.770 --> 00:21:27.820
Don't be shy.

00:21:27.820 --> 00:21:28.780
That looks good.

00:21:28.780 --> 00:21:29.980
Thinly sliced red onion.

00:21:29.980 --> 00:21:31.150
And don't freak out.

00:21:31.150 --> 00:21:32.080
The kids liked it.

00:21:32.080 --> 00:21:33.400
My kids love this.

00:21:33.400 --> 00:21:35.370
Top of that, mozzarella.

00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:36.670
Put a bunch.

00:21:36.670 --> 00:21:38.115
The oven's ready, 450.

00:21:38.115 --> 00:21:39.370
Let's put this on a pan.

00:21:42.940 --> 00:21:45.300
This is going to go in for
about 10 or 12 minutes.

00:21:49.430 --> 00:21:49.930
Bingo.

00:21:49.930 --> 00:21:53.414
When it comes out, it's
going to be awesome.

00:21:53.414 --> 00:21:55.314
OK, it's been 12
minutes exactly.

00:21:55.314 --> 00:21:57.230
Let's pull our pizza out
and see how it looks.

00:22:01.260 --> 00:22:03.690
See, that's just perfect.

00:22:03.690 --> 00:22:04.400
Put it on here.

00:22:07.170 --> 00:22:09.491
We're just going to cut it
because that's what you do.

00:22:12.200 --> 00:22:16.310
You can use one of those
pizza wheel cutters,

00:22:16.310 --> 00:22:18.688
but I just like to
use a regular knife.

00:22:22.040 --> 00:22:23.900
I think the last
thing I'm going to do

00:22:23.900 --> 00:22:26.960
is I would throw just a
little fresh, chopped cilantro

00:22:26.960 --> 00:22:27.995
on the top of this.

00:22:27.995 --> 00:22:31.065
We'll take one bite just so
you can see I eat my own food.

00:22:31.065 --> 00:22:32.965
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:22:36.290 --> 00:22:38.230
Maybe we won't take one bite.

00:22:38.230 --> 00:22:40.370
It's awesome.

00:22:40.370 --> 00:22:43.370
I'm the cooking guy.

00:22:43.370 --> 00:22:45.489
I'll see you next time.

00:22:45.489 --> 00:22:46.030
- Very, cool.

00:22:46.030 --> 00:22:46.640
- There he is.

00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:49.530
- We want to welcome Sam,
the cooking guy, to the show.

00:22:49.530 --> 00:22:50.160
- Thank you.

00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:51.277
[END PLAYBACK]

00:22:51.277 --> 00:22:52.110
SAM ZIEN: All right.

00:22:52.110 --> 00:22:55.770
So they asked me, where did
you learn to cook, your mom?

00:22:55.770 --> 00:22:58.980
I go, my mom is a great cook.

00:22:58.980 --> 00:23:03.300
I take the tape and I send it to
her, a VHS, and send it to her.

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:04.790
She calls me up and she goes--

00:23:04.790 --> 00:23:05.370
I go, hello?

00:23:05.370 --> 00:23:07.661
She goes, I was a good cook?

00:23:07.661 --> 00:23:08.160
I go, what?

00:23:08.160 --> 00:23:08.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:08.460 --> 00:23:09.668
She goes, I watched the tape.

00:23:09.668 --> 00:23:10.830
You said I was a good cook.

00:23:10.830 --> 00:23:11.425
I go, no, mom.

00:23:11.425 --> 00:23:12.550
I said you're a great cook.

00:23:12.550 --> 00:23:13.924
She goes, you said
I was a good--

00:23:13.924 --> 00:23:16.400
I'm not arguing with my mother
about what I said on TV.

00:23:16.400 --> 00:23:24.330
So a year after these segments,
we win two Emmys, a local Emmy.

00:23:24.330 --> 00:23:27.870
Same statue, but it can't
be seen by more than 50%

00:23:27.870 --> 00:23:29.010
of the country.

00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:31.185
You win Emmys for 90
seconds of television.

00:23:31.185 --> 00:23:33.930
It's fantastic.

00:23:33.930 --> 00:23:36.210
I was like, hey, what?

00:23:36.210 --> 00:23:41.640
You can win Emmys for a
commercial's length of stuff?

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:43.950
So then it becomes
a half-hour show.

00:23:43.950 --> 00:23:47.010
By the way, this whole
year that I'm doing this,

00:23:47.010 --> 00:23:49.770
I'm not making a cent.

00:23:49.770 --> 00:23:51.060
They didn't offer me money.

00:23:51.060 --> 00:23:53.020
I didn't ask for money.

00:23:53.020 --> 00:23:54.930
It's not that I'm
independently wealthy,

00:23:54.930 --> 00:23:57.870
but I knew I needed them
more than they needed me.

00:23:57.870 --> 00:23:59.910
They actually kicked
a guy, a chef, off

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:02.757
of their channel to put me in.

00:24:02.757 --> 00:24:04.590
And I don't think it
was because I was free,

00:24:04.590 --> 00:24:06.730
I think it was because
I was different.

00:24:06.730 --> 00:24:09.070
I wasn't the same.

00:24:09.070 --> 00:24:14.880
So then, it becomes a half-hour
show that was produced,

00:24:14.880 --> 00:24:20.440
shot, edited by channel 6 and
the county television network,

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:22.590
shared.

00:24:22.590 --> 00:24:24.810
After a year, that
won two Emmys.

00:24:24.810 --> 00:24:28.170
Like holy smokes, this
Emmy thing is fun.

00:24:28.170 --> 00:24:29.544
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:33.210 --> 00:24:37.920
The general manager of
channel 6 at the time

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:39.030
takes me in his office.

00:24:39.030 --> 00:24:41.040
I'm eventually making money.

00:24:41.040 --> 00:24:43.230
By the time the
first year ends, I'm

00:24:43.230 --> 00:24:45.700
making a couple hundred
dollars each time these things

00:24:45.700 --> 00:24:49.200
air, so like 400 bucks a
week, which is excellent.

00:24:49.200 --> 00:24:51.480
And when the half-hour
show-- he sits me down.

00:24:51.480 --> 00:24:52.090
He goes, here's what
we're going to do.

00:24:52.090 --> 00:24:53.589
We're going to pay
you the same way.

00:24:53.589 --> 00:24:55.680
Every time it airs,
you're going to get this.

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:58.110
First time I get a paycheck
after the half hour

00:24:58.110 --> 00:25:01.710
show starts airing, there's
no half-hour money on it.

00:25:01.710 --> 00:25:03.800
I call the payroll
people and they go,

00:25:03.800 --> 00:25:05.430
oh, he just needs to tell us.

00:25:05.430 --> 00:25:06.600
We'll get it going.

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:07.342
I call him up.

00:25:07.342 --> 00:25:08.550
I say, hey, blah, blah, blah.

00:25:08.550 --> 00:25:10.556
He goes, I never said that.

00:25:10.556 --> 00:25:12.180
I go, wait, sorry,
you never said what?

00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:15.250
He goes, I never said I'd pay
you for the half-hour shows.

00:25:15.250 --> 00:25:16.605
Well, I stood in your office.

00:25:16.605 --> 00:25:17.730
You were at the flip chart.

00:25:17.730 --> 00:25:18.480
You did the thing.

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:19.980
We had the whole conversation.

00:25:19.980 --> 00:25:20.830
Al was there.

00:25:20.830 --> 00:25:23.750
He goes, I never
said I would pay you.

00:25:23.750 --> 00:25:25.530
I go, oh, OK.

00:25:25.530 --> 00:25:26.642
Hang up the phone.

00:25:26.642 --> 00:25:29.100
Now, I start finding out that
this guy-- this is this guy's

00:25:29.100 --> 00:25:30.180
MO.

00:25:30.180 --> 00:25:32.190
Says one thing,
does something else.

00:25:32.190 --> 00:25:33.390
Pretends to be religious.

00:25:33.390 --> 00:25:34.890
He's a religious guy.

00:25:34.890 --> 00:25:38.550
His denomination doesn't matter,
but he wore it like a jacket,

00:25:38.550 --> 00:25:42.390
except he was a piece
of you know what.

00:25:42.390 --> 00:25:44.100
Say one thing, do
something else.

00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:46.260
I said, I won't work
for this guy anymore.

00:25:46.260 --> 00:25:48.210
But I know if I walk
up to him and say

00:25:48.210 --> 00:25:50.347
I'm going to quit
in two weeks, he's

00:25:50.347 --> 00:25:51.930
going to say, tell
you what, quit now.

00:25:51.930 --> 00:25:53.256
You're done.

00:25:53.256 --> 00:25:55.380
And I didn't want to just
go quietly into the night

00:25:55.380 --> 00:25:58.740
and not have people that were
following my segments on TV

00:25:58.740 --> 00:26:00.210
just think that I'd quit.

00:26:00.210 --> 00:26:04.260
Because social media
15, 14 years ago

00:26:04.260 --> 00:26:06.720
wasn't really like it is now.

00:26:06.720 --> 00:26:09.610
I didn't have a huge following.

00:26:09.610 --> 00:26:12.900
So I decided I would take
myself off the air myself.

00:26:12.900 --> 00:26:15.270
So one day-- it's a Friday.

00:26:15.270 --> 00:26:16.820
And just as the
segment's ending,

00:26:16.820 --> 00:26:17.895
I'm sitting there
talking to the anchors.

00:26:17.895 --> 00:26:18.900
And I go, guess what?

00:26:18.900 --> 00:26:19.410
Big news.

00:26:19.410 --> 00:26:19.993
They go, what?

00:26:19.993 --> 00:26:20.790
I go, next Friday.

00:26:20.790 --> 00:26:21.510
They go, yeah?

00:26:21.510 --> 00:26:23.070
I go, is my last day.

00:26:23.070 --> 00:26:25.260
By the time I got home,
there was an email,

00:26:25.260 --> 00:26:26.310
don't bother coming back.

00:26:26.310 --> 00:26:29.400
But at least I got
to say my last day.

00:26:29.400 --> 00:26:34.980
So now, along comes
the Discovery Networks

00:26:34.980 --> 00:26:35.890
to do a show.

00:26:35.890 --> 00:26:38.140
Would you be interested
in doing a show?

00:26:38.140 --> 00:26:39.630
Of course I would.

00:26:39.630 --> 00:26:41.790
So we shot something
called "Just Cook This"

00:26:41.790 --> 00:26:43.170
with Sam the cooking guy.

00:26:43.170 --> 00:26:45.750
And they go, but
Discovery Health

00:26:45.750 --> 00:26:47.790
is the network it will air on.

00:26:47.790 --> 00:26:48.960
We like to do healthy stuff.

00:26:48.960 --> 00:26:50.841
What would your angle be?

00:26:50.841 --> 00:26:52.965
Because it's not like you're
known for health food.

00:26:52.965 --> 00:26:54.310
I go, it would be this.

00:26:54.310 --> 00:26:55.200
Here's a pizza.

00:26:55.200 --> 00:26:57.570
Here's lots of cheese and
pepperoni, stuff like this.

00:26:57.570 --> 00:26:58.960
Don't eat the whole thing.

00:26:58.960 --> 00:26:59.770
The guy laughed.

00:26:59.770 --> 00:27:00.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:00.270 --> 00:27:03.450
And he bought it
and I had a show.

00:27:03.450 --> 00:27:06.470
It was kind of that.

00:27:06.470 --> 00:27:09.690
Until Oprah came along and
bought, literally bought,

00:27:09.690 --> 00:27:12.300
the Discovery Health
number on the dial

00:27:12.300 --> 00:27:16.860
everywhere and turned it into
the Oprah Winfrey Network, OWN.

00:27:16.860 --> 00:27:20.430
And I'm not bitter that she
had to have her own freaking

00:27:20.430 --> 00:27:24.840
network and felt that her people
felt that my stuff was too

00:27:24.840 --> 00:27:27.040
male oriented.

00:27:27.040 --> 00:27:28.560
But it's not.

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:30.930
I mean, I think a lot of
guys watch my show, maybe

00:27:30.930 --> 00:27:34.330
more than generally watch
straight cooking shows.

00:27:34.330 --> 00:27:37.790
But still, the predominance
of my audience is female.

00:27:37.790 --> 00:27:38.790
No, they didn't like me.

00:27:38.790 --> 00:27:40.560
So that's fine.

00:27:40.560 --> 00:27:44.460
Meanwhile, a publisher
comes along and says, would

00:27:44.460 --> 00:27:45.633
you like to do a cookbook?

00:27:45.633 --> 00:27:49.160
I'd love to do a cookbook.

00:27:49.160 --> 00:27:50.880
Cookbook comes
out, the first one.

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:53.605
There's now three.

00:27:53.605 --> 00:27:57.510
They go, we got you a
spot on the "Today Show."

00:27:57.510 --> 00:27:59.960
That's fantastic,
the "Today Show."

00:27:59.960 --> 00:28:01.269
It's great.

00:28:01.269 --> 00:28:02.310
I go to the "Today Show."

00:28:02.310 --> 00:28:04.160
It's in New York.

00:28:04.160 --> 00:28:05.990
It's a big deal.

00:28:05.990 --> 00:28:10.220
Matt Lauer had not been
fingered as a bad guy yet.

00:28:10.220 --> 00:28:13.390
America was so
innocent in those days.

00:28:13.390 --> 00:28:14.390
I do the segment.

00:28:14.390 --> 00:28:20.030
I'm making chicken enchiladas,
white chicken enchiladas.

00:28:20.030 --> 00:28:21.140
They're on the website.

00:28:21.140 --> 00:28:23.030
They're in my first cookbook.

00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:25.730
There's cream and
there's cheese.

00:28:25.730 --> 00:28:29.766
And Hoda Kotb, in the
middle of this as I'm

00:28:29.766 --> 00:28:31.640
putting cream and cheese
in, she goes, uh oh.

00:28:31.640 --> 00:28:32.640
I go, what?

00:28:32.640 --> 00:28:36.470
There's a lot of something
there, a lot of fat.

00:28:36.470 --> 00:28:41.000
I go, well, if a recipe
says, serves six, it should.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:43.170
Don't eat the whole
thing yourself.

00:28:43.170 --> 00:28:45.770
Second I say that, I said, don't
eat the whole frickin' thing

00:28:45.770 --> 00:28:46.490
yourself.

00:28:46.490 --> 00:28:47.930
The crew laughs.

00:28:47.930 --> 00:28:50.720
And I think, uh oh, is this
bad that I've said "frickin' "

00:28:50.720 --> 00:28:52.010
on the "Today Show?"

00:28:52.010 --> 00:28:53.270
Segment ends.

00:28:53.270 --> 00:28:55.790
I'm walking down the
street with my wife.

00:28:55.790 --> 00:29:00.380
I get a text from the "Today
Show," two important questions.

00:29:00.380 --> 00:29:01.850
Can you come back
in three weeks?

00:29:05.330 --> 00:29:06.636
My wife's like, what, what?

00:29:06.636 --> 00:29:08.700
I go, they want me back.

00:29:08.700 --> 00:29:10.022
She goes, they do?

00:29:10.022 --> 00:29:11.230
Well, thanks for the support.

00:29:11.230 --> 00:29:12.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:12.450 --> 00:29:15.670
Yeah, they do.

00:29:15.670 --> 00:29:18.040
I go, and there's
another question.

00:29:18.040 --> 00:29:19.210
She goes, what?

00:29:19.210 --> 00:29:19.780
I don't know.

00:29:19.780 --> 00:29:20.571
It's not important.

00:29:20.571 --> 00:29:23.107
She goes, what is it?

00:29:23.107 --> 00:29:23.690
And I read it.

00:29:23.690 --> 00:29:26.500
She goes, everybody
here wants to know

00:29:26.500 --> 00:29:29.032
where your wife got her boots.

00:29:29.032 --> 00:29:30.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:30.310 --> 00:29:31.360
So here's the moral.

00:29:31.360 --> 00:29:34.490
Just when you think
it's all about you,

00:29:34.490 --> 00:29:36.610
it's about your wife's boots.

00:29:36.610 --> 00:29:38.540
Anyway, I go back.

00:29:38.540 --> 00:29:40.240
I go back.

00:29:40.240 --> 00:29:43.024
And here's my second
time on the "Today Show."

