1, 2, 3, 4 ingredients.

00:38:27.136 --> 00:38:28.510
We've got the
raspberries in here

00:38:28.510 --> 00:38:31.695
that went in frozen, the cake,
the peaches in heavy syrup,

00:38:31.695 --> 00:38:33.820
a little bit of butter over
the top, and that's it.

00:38:33.820 --> 00:38:34.660
Bingo, we're done.

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:36.940
In fact, they call it
a reality cooking show.

00:38:36.940 --> 00:38:40.450
Whatever really happens when
we shoot stays in the show.

00:38:40.450 --> 00:38:41.340
Oh, oh.

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:46.600
Hot, really hot.

00:38:46.600 --> 00:38:47.620
Welcome back to the zoo.

00:38:50.956 --> 00:38:53.130
[LAUGHS] Ready for this move?

00:38:53.130 --> 00:38:53.630
Here we go.

00:38:53.630 --> 00:38:55.598
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:38:57.566 --> 00:38:58.310
Nice.

00:38:58.310 --> 00:39:00.310
We're going to take them
and we're going to go--

00:39:03.260 --> 00:39:05.230
Hi, I'm Rachael Ray.

00:39:05.230 --> 00:39:07.240
And welcome to
"30 Minute Meals."

00:39:07.240 --> 00:39:08.360
Oh god.

00:39:08.360 --> 00:39:09.510
Whoa, whoa.

00:39:09.510 --> 00:39:11.220
And unlike some
other cooking shows,

00:39:11.220 --> 00:39:12.510
there's no fancy ingredients.

00:39:12.510 --> 00:39:15.990
In fact, everything comes from
a regular, everyday supermarket.

00:39:15.990 --> 00:39:17.520
So we had this idea.

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:19.710
We thought we'd do a
whole show about potatoes

00:39:19.710 --> 00:39:23.320
because everybody
likes potatoes, right?

00:39:23.320 --> 00:39:27.560
Ready bacon, one of my
favorite things ever.

00:39:27.560 --> 00:39:29.040
We did pesto.

00:39:29.040 --> 00:39:32.440
We did the goat
cheese, tomatoes,

00:39:32.440 --> 00:39:34.450
the melted mozzarella.

00:39:34.450 --> 00:39:35.730
This thing, two ingredients.

00:39:35.730 --> 00:39:37.170
Come on, let's get going.

00:39:37.170 --> 00:39:39.570
And the line that I use,
things that are big in taste

00:39:39.570 --> 00:39:40.980
and small in effort.

00:39:40.980 --> 00:39:42.240
Come on now.

00:39:42.240 --> 00:39:44.300
This is crazy good.

00:39:44.300 --> 00:39:46.850
You have no idea how
good these guys smell.

00:39:46.850 --> 00:39:49.500
Cocoa powder on top,
and then the last thing,

00:39:49.500 --> 00:39:51.450
a little bit more of
the powdered sugar.

00:39:51.450 --> 00:39:53.680
That makes the cocoa
powder look pretty.

00:39:53.680 --> 00:39:55.500
It's perfect.

00:39:55.500 --> 00:39:57.180
We've done a good
job here today.

00:39:57.180 --> 00:39:59.754
And unlike other
stand-and-stir cooking shows,

00:39:59.754 --> 00:40:01.170
we don't just stay
in the kitchen.

00:40:01.170 --> 00:40:02.070
We get out.

00:40:02.070 --> 00:40:04.990
We really get out.

00:40:04.990 --> 00:40:07.820
Today is Sam the
Cooking Guy out at sea

00:40:07.820 --> 00:40:09.610
with the USS Ronald Reagan.

00:40:09.610 --> 00:40:13.750
Today, we're starting our cool
kitchens on the Light Star.

00:40:13.750 --> 00:40:15.820
It's time for the San
Diego County Fair.

00:40:15.820 --> 00:40:18.190
Today, we're having
a ball inside.

00:40:18.190 --> 00:40:18.910
Let's go.

00:40:18.910 --> 00:40:20.320
Come on, everybody.

00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:24.010
Let's not just cook with
the coconut oil from Fiji,

00:40:24.010 --> 00:40:26.850
let's go to Fiji.

00:40:26.850 --> 00:40:27.880
And we did.

00:40:27.880 --> 00:40:30.430
So it only seems right, since
we're in the Mexican Riviera,

00:40:30.430 --> 00:40:32.710
we do some Mexican
Riviera kind of cocktail.

00:40:32.710 --> 00:40:35.680
This is my hometown,
Vancouver, British Columbia.

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:36.740
I love this place.

00:40:36.740 --> 00:40:38.020
I grew up in this place.

00:40:38.020 --> 00:40:40.200
I've been watching the
food on the "Today Show"

00:40:40.200 --> 00:40:41.190
while in Vancouver.

00:40:41.190 --> 00:40:43.120
And it's been nice, but
it was time somebody

00:40:43.120 --> 00:40:46.030
did this, something that
everybody could make.

00:40:46.030 --> 00:40:49.010
I say this is Canada's
culinary gift to the world.

00:40:49.010 --> 00:40:49.900
And so that's it.

00:40:49.900 --> 00:40:52.370
Lots of entertainment,
great food, tons of fun.

00:40:52.370 --> 00:40:53.930
I mean, what more do you
want out of a cooking show?

00:40:53.930 --> 00:40:55.850
Why hasn't somebody
thought of this already?

00:40:55.850 --> 00:40:58.174
I have no idea.

00:40:58.174 --> 00:40:59.170
What?

00:40:59.170 --> 00:40:59.990
What?

00:40:59.990 --> 00:41:02.610
Oh.

00:41:02.610 --> 00:41:08.105
Somebody put the-- honey, The
Emmys are in the fridge again.

00:41:08.105 --> 00:41:09.030
(WHISPERS) My bad.

00:41:09.030 --> 00:41:09.990
So sorry.

00:41:09.990 --> 00:41:12.750
Aw, geez.

00:41:12.750 --> 00:41:14.080
[END PLAYBACK]

00:41:14.080 --> 00:41:17.380
So that's a bunch
of years, but it's

00:41:17.380 --> 00:41:22.090
being happy and comfortable
and really liking what you do.

00:41:22.090 --> 00:41:24.250
And I get to wake up.

00:41:24.250 --> 00:41:26.790
I mean, A, I don't have
a very far commute.

00:41:26.790 --> 00:41:29.030
It's downstairs.

00:41:29.030 --> 00:41:32.380
And I get to do all
kinds of fun stuff.

00:41:32.380 --> 00:41:35.870
We've shot three shows with the
Navy, two on aircraft carriers,

00:41:35.870 --> 00:41:38.410
and one on a fast
attack nuclear sub

00:41:38.410 --> 00:41:42.190
that we got to spend 24
hours on each one of them.

00:41:42.190 --> 00:41:45.740
And the Navy is amazing.

00:41:45.740 --> 00:41:48.820
It's nothing but
practice, get your game

00:41:48.820 --> 00:41:51.130
down perfect for
the moment when you

00:41:51.130 --> 00:41:54.560
have to be able to do everything
without even thinking about it.

00:41:54.560 --> 00:41:56.020
It's really spectacular.

00:41:56.020 --> 00:41:59.050
There's nothing like being on
the deck of an aircraft carrier

00:41:59.050 --> 00:42:01.720
with those things landing
right in front of you.

00:42:01.720 --> 00:42:03.300
It's unbelievable.

00:42:05.950 --> 00:42:09.070
And the only part that had
been sort of-ish lacking

00:42:09.070 --> 00:42:10.070
is the restaurant thing.

00:42:10.070 --> 00:42:12.520
And I get that
question all the time.

00:42:12.520 --> 00:42:13.420
Sorry.

00:42:13.420 --> 00:42:17.230
And finally, we'll answer it.

00:42:17.230 --> 00:42:20.770
We're going to open a very
small thing this summer

00:42:20.770 --> 00:42:24.190
in what will become the
new Little Italy food hall.

00:42:24.190 --> 00:42:26.650
There will be six
restaurants in there.

00:42:26.650 --> 00:42:30.574
Mine is called "Not Not
Tacos" because they're tacos,

00:42:30.574 --> 00:42:31.990
but they're not
tacos in the sense

00:42:31.990 --> 00:42:34.060
that they're carnitas
or carne asada

00:42:34.060 --> 00:42:37.360
or pollo or chorizo,
nothing Mexican.

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:41.650
It will be things like
Asian salmon and pastrami

00:42:41.650 --> 00:42:44.530
with crispy onions and
melted cheese and coleslaw,

00:42:44.530 --> 00:42:47.950
an over-easy egg on top
and that kind of stuff.

00:42:50.480 --> 00:42:54.972
So that's all I got, really.

00:42:54.972 --> 00:42:56.180
FRANCESCA: Thank you so much.

00:42:56.180 --> 00:42:57.659
Do we have any questions?

00:42:57.659 --> 00:42:59.631
[APPLAUSE]

00:43:02.096 --> 00:43:03.580
Questions, guys?

00:43:03.580 --> 00:43:07.550
SAM ZIEN: We believe it'll be
June 25, last week of June.

00:43:07.550 --> 00:43:10.990
But there's six places
that have to all be ready,

00:43:10.990 --> 00:43:13.080
and the project itself.

00:43:13.080 --> 00:43:16.600
They've closed off Date Street
between India and Columbia.

00:43:16.600 --> 00:43:21.970
It's now a piazza, Piazza della
Famiglia, with a giant fountain

00:43:21.970 --> 00:43:25.155
there, really beautiful
spot, beautiful location.

00:43:25.155 --> 00:43:26.530
So all the rest
of this stuff has

00:43:26.530 --> 00:43:28.360
got to be done
before health permits

00:43:28.360 --> 00:43:29.540
and all that stuff happens.

00:43:29.540 --> 00:43:32.500
But it's looking like it's
going to be a good thing.

00:43:32.500 --> 00:43:33.000
Yeah.

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:34.240
It's fun.

00:43:34.240 --> 00:43:36.650
Do what you love, the money
will follow or something.

00:43:36.650 --> 00:43:37.150
Yes, sir?

00:43:37.150 --> 00:43:38.274
AUDIENCE: --daily expenses?

00:43:38.274 --> 00:43:40.030
SAM ZIEN: How did I
afford daily expenses

00:43:40.030 --> 00:43:41.470
when I wasn't making any money?

00:43:41.470 --> 00:43:42.544
Because I didn't.

00:43:42.544 --> 00:43:44.210
That first year, I
didn't make anything.

00:43:44.210 --> 00:43:46.750
The second year, I think
I made $16,000, which

00:43:46.750 --> 00:43:49.597
averaged out to $8,000 a year.

00:43:49.597 --> 00:43:50.680
OK, I'm going to admit it.

00:43:50.680 --> 00:43:53.413
I was part of the
housing crisis problem.

00:43:53.413 --> 00:43:54.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:54.100 --> 00:43:55.690
The banking issue.

00:43:55.690 --> 00:43:58.540
I pulled money out
of my house that I

00:43:58.540 --> 00:44:00.640
wish I still had in my house.

00:44:00.640 --> 00:44:03.490
But those were the
days when you could

00:44:03.490 --> 00:44:15.760
get a loan from the bank to buy
a house with seemingly nothing.

00:44:15.760 --> 00:44:19.570
You have a job, you
have warm blood, fine.

00:44:19.570 --> 00:44:23.020
We'll give you a couple hundred
thousand dollars for a house.

00:44:23.020 --> 00:44:24.730
That's what I did.

00:44:24.730 --> 00:44:26.740
My wife worked.

00:44:26.740 --> 00:44:28.240
And so that's not
completely true.

00:44:28.240 --> 00:44:29.980
So my wife worked, that's true.

00:44:29.980 --> 00:44:33.700
But I continued to consult for
biotech for a couple of years

00:44:33.700 --> 00:44:35.000
after that.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.270
So I made money that way.

00:44:37.270 --> 00:44:37.870
I hated it.

00:44:37.870 --> 00:44:39.610
I was miserable.

00:44:39.610 --> 00:44:42.940
What struck me, as Francesca
was walking me around today

00:44:42.940 --> 00:44:47.126
and we got to your tap room--

00:44:47.126 --> 00:44:48.000
and I'm just curious.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:51.310
I go, are there limitations,
have all the beer you want,

00:44:51.310 --> 00:44:52.810
but after four
o'clock or something?

00:44:52.810 --> 00:44:56.170
She goes, no, doesn't matter.

00:44:56.170 --> 00:44:59.530
So I went from being
the facilities manager

00:44:59.530 --> 00:45:02.780
to the director of operations
at the biotech company.

00:45:02.780 --> 00:45:05.080
We're about 125 people.

00:45:05.080 --> 00:45:06.640
I reported directly
to the president.

00:45:06.640 --> 00:45:08.800
And I go to him one day
and I go, got an idea.

00:45:08.800 --> 00:45:11.350
We had a small campus,
four buildings.

00:45:11.350 --> 00:45:15.720
And I go, I'm going to
put a basketball hoop

00:45:15.720 --> 00:45:18.400
in between the engineering
and the, whatever, biology

00:45:18.400 --> 00:45:19.150
building.

00:45:19.150 --> 00:45:25.580
And he looks at me and he
goes, well, what's that for?

00:45:25.580 --> 00:45:30.010
And I go, it's for basketball.

00:45:30.010 --> 00:45:31.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:31.870 --> 00:45:35.650
And he goes, why are
you putting it there?

00:45:35.650 --> 00:45:37.615
I go, because a couple
of people have asked.

00:45:37.615 --> 00:45:38.740
I think it's a great thing.

00:45:38.740 --> 00:45:40.730
You go blow off a little steam.

00:45:40.730 --> 00:45:43.541
He goes, we're not putting
a basketball hoop in.

00:45:43.541 --> 00:45:46.700
I go, I want you to
think about this.

00:45:46.700 --> 00:45:47.455
It's good.

00:45:47.455 --> 00:45:51.760
He goes, I don't want that
scientist spending all his time

00:45:51.760 --> 00:45:54.520
playing basketball, not
being at the bench working.

00:45:54.520 --> 00:45:57.190
I said, he doesn't
report to you.

00:45:57.190 --> 00:46:00.995
He has his own boss, the
director of chemistry.

00:46:00.995 --> 00:46:01.870
And think about this.

00:46:01.870 --> 00:46:03.580
Two things are going to happen.

00:46:03.580 --> 00:46:07.230
He spends all his day
time playing basketball

00:46:07.230 --> 00:46:09.540
and now, we know the
guy does nothing.

00:46:09.540 --> 00:46:11.650
And he gets fired.

00:46:11.650 --> 00:46:14.500
We're getting rid of
terrible dead wood.

00:46:14.500 --> 00:46:18.880
Or he's working on a really
complex chemical reaction.

00:46:18.880 --> 00:46:21.430
He's having trouble
making it come together.

00:46:21.430 --> 00:46:24.450
He needs to clear his head
instead of sitting at his desk

00:46:24.450 --> 00:46:26.200
and looking at chemistry books.

00:46:26.200 --> 00:46:26.920
He goes outside.

00:46:26.920 --> 00:46:31.120
He plays hoops for 15 minutes
or Horse by himself or whatever.

00:46:31.120 --> 00:46:31.810
It comes to him.

00:46:31.810 --> 00:46:34.570
He comes inside and he
fixes it, and it works.

00:46:34.570 --> 00:46:35.740
That's success.

00:46:35.740 --> 00:46:37.900
Either case, it's success.

00:46:37.900 --> 00:46:40.780
And he goes, oh, OK.

00:46:40.780 --> 00:46:42.820
We're not putting a
basketball hoop any time

00:46:42.820 --> 00:46:45.040
while I'm president
of this company.

00:46:45.040 --> 00:46:47.560
That was the day I
said I need to leave.

00:46:47.560 --> 00:46:49.480
I won't work for this guy.

00:46:49.480 --> 00:46:51.026
It took me two years
to actually pull

00:46:51.026 --> 00:46:52.900
the trigger on the whole
thing and figure out

00:46:52.900 --> 00:46:56.140
because I didn't want to just
go to another biotech company.

00:46:56.140 --> 00:46:58.887
But just look at how
far things have come.

00:46:58.887 --> 00:47:00.970
Honestly, I don't think
that guy would do anything

00:47:00.970 --> 00:47:02.125
different today.

00:47:02.125 --> 00:47:03.474
He was like that.

00:47:03.474 --> 00:47:04.890
And he knows how
I feel about him.

00:47:04.890 --> 00:47:07.150
We've talked about,
this is ridiculous.

00:47:07.150 --> 00:47:11.380
But hopefully you guys are in
a good spot, great company,

00:47:11.380 --> 00:47:14.200
doing things that
you really like.

00:47:14.200 --> 00:47:16.836
And if you don't, then quit
and just don't mention my name.

00:47:16.836 --> 00:47:18.002
I had nothing to do with it.

00:47:18.002 --> 00:47:19.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:20.400 --> 00:47:21.400
I'll tell you something.

00:47:21.400 --> 00:47:21.983
You know what?

00:47:21.983 --> 00:47:25.150
So when I had the idea
to do the cooking show

00:47:25.150 --> 00:47:27.910
and then I started looking
for a kitchen, remember,

00:47:27.910 --> 00:47:29.770
I only knew what I saw on TV.

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:34.800
So I went looking for a kitchen
that looked like a kitchen

00:47:34.800 --> 00:47:37.116
in a cooking show studio.

00:47:37.116 --> 00:47:38.740
AUDIENCE: I'd think
that would ruin it.

00:47:38.740 --> 00:47:40.031
SAM ZIEN: So here's what I did.

00:47:40.031 --> 00:47:42.280
I took my real
estate background,

00:47:42.280 --> 00:47:44.320
and I went to a lot of
the real estate offices

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:47.650
and I gave them flyers, the
tony, fancy ones, Rancho Santa

00:47:47.650 --> 00:47:49.287
Fe, Del Mar, Fairbanks Ranch.

00:47:49.287 --> 00:47:51.370
Do you have a client that
would like their kitchen

00:47:51.370 --> 00:47:53.810
to be featured in
a TV show pilot?

00:47:53.810 --> 00:47:54.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:54.610 --> 00:47:55.690
It wasn't a pilot.

00:47:55.690 --> 00:47:56.740
It was nothing.

00:47:56.740 --> 00:47:59.170
It was a dream.

00:47:59.170 --> 00:48:01.360
It was as close to
being a pilot as me

00:48:01.360 --> 00:48:04.180
dreaming about having kids
one day when I was like 18.

00:48:04.180 --> 00:48:05.530
I'm going to have kids one day.

00:48:05.530 --> 00:48:07.051
It was that.

00:48:07.051 --> 00:48:08.800
And I went and I looked
at a few kitchens.

00:48:08.800 --> 00:48:12.850
And there's always something
wrong, too many windows,

00:48:12.850 --> 00:48:17.380
not too many windows,
but ugly countertops.

00:48:17.380 --> 00:48:21.550
So I'm sitting in my kitchen
one day, my older kitchen,

00:48:21.550 --> 00:48:23.470
writing notes about
what I needed to do.

00:48:23.470 --> 00:48:26.675
And there was a
moment, I'm thinking.

00:48:26.675 --> 00:48:27.550
I look at my kitchen.

00:48:27.550 --> 00:48:29.650
I go, this show's
for regular people.

00:48:29.650 --> 00:48:33.260
I don't want a 2,000 square
foot kitchen in Rancho Santa Fe

00:48:33.260 --> 00:48:33.760
home.

00:48:33.760 --> 00:48:35.710
I want my kitchen.

00:48:35.710 --> 00:48:37.330
So that made sense.

00:48:37.330 --> 00:48:40.990
Cutting myself, leaving that
in when I do that on the show

00:48:40.990 --> 00:48:42.070
made sense.

00:48:42.070 --> 00:48:44.200
I heard that Rachael Ray,
one of her first times

00:48:44.200 --> 00:48:47.620
on her show, "30 Minute
Meals," she cut herself.

00:48:47.620 --> 00:48:49.720
They stop the tape.

00:48:49.720 --> 00:48:51.370
They got the blood off.

00:48:51.370 --> 00:48:52.570
They Krazy Glued it--

00:48:52.570 --> 00:48:53.615
which you can do that.

00:48:53.615 --> 00:48:56.003
It won't hurt you.

00:48:56.003 --> 00:48:57.750
I've done it so many times.

00:48:57.750 --> 00:49:00.130
They Krazy Glued her finger,
put a little makeup on it,

00:49:00.130 --> 00:49:01.713
rolled the tape back,
and then carried

00:49:01.713 --> 00:49:03.984
on like it didn't happen.

00:49:03.984 --> 00:49:05.650
Well, if I drop
something or burn myself

00:49:05.650 --> 00:49:08.290
or whatever, that to me, is--

00:49:08.290 --> 00:49:10.382
I said it-- reality
cooking show.

00:49:10.382 --> 00:49:12.340
But you have to specify
reality because there's

00:49:12.340 --> 00:49:14.510
a lot of fake
reality these days.

00:49:14.510 --> 00:49:21.760
You're not going to find 10
white supremacists with a 10

00:49:21.760 --> 00:49:25.775
all-black church choir on the
same little island that have

00:49:25.775 --> 00:49:27.955
to live together for 10 days.

00:49:27.955 --> 00:49:29.080
That's not going to happen.

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:30.280
That's not reality.

00:49:30.280 --> 00:49:33.190
That's made up stuff
that producers force.

00:49:33.190 --> 00:49:34.840
This is realistic.

00:49:34.840 --> 00:49:37.870
If my doorbell rings in
the middle of the show,

00:49:37.870 --> 00:49:40.465
I might yell at whoever it is,
but we leave that kind of stuff

00:49:40.465 --> 00:49:40.970
in.

00:49:40.970 --> 00:49:42.130
And that's when people
will come up and go,

00:49:42.130 --> 00:49:44.020
you make me feel
like I can cook,

00:49:44.020 --> 00:49:47.110
like you've given me license
to screw up and make mistakes.

00:49:47.110 --> 00:49:48.370
Well, that's what it is.

00:49:48.370 --> 00:49:50.950
That's what cooking is.

00:49:50.950 --> 00:49:54.416
Until you start doing it,
don't stay out of a kitchen

00:49:54.416 --> 00:49:56.540
because you don't think
that you can make mistakes.

00:49:56.540 --> 00:49:57.040
You can.

00:49:57.040 --> 00:50:00.660
I make them all the
time, big ones too.

00:50:00.660 --> 00:50:02.650
Lost a piece of the
end of my finger once.

00:50:02.650 --> 00:50:04.630
The crew called it finger
halibut for months.

00:50:04.630 --> 00:50:06.446
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:07.766 --> 00:50:09.390
It was really good
until the end of it.

00:50:09.390 --> 00:50:11.990
And we're like, oh, I do not
know where that piece of finger

00:50:11.990 --> 00:50:12.490
went.

00:50:12.490 --> 00:50:14.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:14.230 --> 00:50:15.370
Seriously.

00:50:15.370 --> 00:50:17.200
It was such a creepy,
horrible moment.

00:50:17.200 --> 00:50:18.928
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:20.990 --> 00:50:21.490
Good.

00:50:21.490 --> 00:50:23.940
AUDIENCE: Is it
still the same crew?

00:50:23.940 --> 00:50:26.110
SAM ZIEN: No, it's changed
so many times since then.

00:50:26.110 --> 00:50:27.550
It really has, yeah.

00:50:27.550 --> 00:50:30.370
But always, the people
have been great.

00:50:30.370 --> 00:50:33.130
And when people have
taken the spot of somebody

00:50:33.130 --> 00:50:36.160
else and they didn't know if
they could do that kind of--

00:50:36.160 --> 00:50:39.790
it's very different
television because apart

00:50:39.790 --> 00:50:41.890
from a very small
period of time,

00:50:41.890 --> 00:50:46.390
it's one camera, which
is a bit of a dance

00:50:46.390 --> 00:50:48.340
that you have to learn.

00:50:48.340 --> 00:50:50.900
Three cameras--
three cameras here.

00:50:50.900 --> 00:50:52.150
There are Food Network shows--

00:50:52.150 --> 00:50:53.590
Tyler Florence had
a show, I can't

00:50:53.590 --> 00:50:55.090
remember what it was called--

00:50:55.090 --> 00:50:58.810
they shot the same
food three times.

00:50:58.810 --> 00:51:02.540
One shot wide, you'd see the
whole kitchen and all of him.

00:51:02.540 --> 00:51:04.540
The second one, you'd see
him from the waist up.

00:51:04.540 --> 00:51:06.800
And the third one,
just his hands.

00:51:06.800 --> 00:51:10.510
And he'd make that same
pasta carbonara three times,

00:51:10.510 --> 00:51:12.250
far, medium, close.

00:51:12.250 --> 00:51:15.070
And then an editor sits
with three separate lines

00:51:15.070 --> 00:51:16.850
and builds it all together.

00:51:16.850 --> 00:51:17.830
I don't like that.

00:51:17.830 --> 00:51:20.800
I like a relationship
with one camera.

00:51:20.800 --> 00:51:23.050
People say, I feel like
you're talking to me.

00:51:23.050 --> 00:51:25.390
And I think that's
because of how we shoot,

00:51:25.390 --> 00:51:27.707
partially me because
I'm weird, whatever,

00:51:27.707 --> 00:51:29.290
but partially because
it's one camera.

00:51:29.290 --> 00:51:33.708
I can look right at that camera
like I'm talking to somebody.

00:51:33.708 --> 00:51:34.333
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:51:34.333 --> 00:51:37.080
It's like the new sitcoms where
they do the single cameras

00:51:37.080 --> 00:51:37.830
like "The Office."

00:51:37.830 --> 00:51:38.496
SAM ZIEN: Right.

00:51:38.496 --> 00:51:40.210
Exactly.

00:51:40.210 --> 00:51:41.310
That's exactly what it is.

00:51:41.310 --> 00:51:44.610
It really works for me.

00:51:44.610 --> 00:51:47.280
I shot an infomercial
last February

00:51:47.280 --> 00:51:49.770
and another one this
past February in Tampa.

00:51:49.770 --> 00:51:51.240
And there were like six cameras.

00:51:51.240 --> 00:51:55.281
And that's a weird
thing to get used to.

00:51:55.281 --> 00:51:57.030
You really have to
know which one at which

00:51:57.030 --> 00:51:58.860
times and there's a lot of this.

00:51:58.860 --> 00:52:00.502
No, that one right now.

00:52:00.502 --> 00:52:01.637
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:01.637 --> 00:52:03.720
And you're looking here
and you hear the snapping,

00:52:03.720 --> 00:52:06.570
and you don't want to
take your gaze off.

00:52:06.570 --> 00:52:07.320
But it's fine.

00:52:07.320 --> 00:52:08.010
It's fine.

00:52:08.010 --> 00:52:08.950
Yeah.

